content:
Minimal fix: separate datasource for reaper (isolate pool), batched delete with LIMIT to cap lock duration, index on expires_at. Checkout pool never sees reaper contention; reaper still runs on schedule.

```yaml
# application.yml — add dedicated maintenance datasource
spring:
  datasource:
    checkout:
      jdbc-url: jdbc:postgresql://db/app
      hikari:
        pool-name: checkout-pool
        maximum-pool-size: 20
        connection-timeout: 5000
    maintenance:
      jdbc-url: jdbc:postgresql://db-replica/app  # or primary if no replica
      hikari:
        pool-name: maintenance-pool
        maximum-pool-size: 2
        connection-timeout: 30000
```

```sql
-- one-time migration: index the reaper's predicate
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_sessions_expires_at
  ON sessions (expires_at)
  WHERE expires_at IS NOT NULL;
```

```java
// SessionReaper.java — bounded batches, short txns, own datasource
@Component
public class SessionReaper {
  private static final int BATCH_SIZE = 5_000;
  private static final Duration BATCH_PAUSE = Duration.ofMillis(200);

  @Qualifier("maintenanceJdbcTemplate")
  private final JdbcTemplate jdbc;

  @Scheduled(cron = "0 */5 * * * *")
  public void reap() {
    int deleted;
    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
    do {
      deleted = jdbc.update(
        "DELETE FROM sessions WHERE ctid IN (" +
        "  SELECT ctid FROM sessions " +
        "  WHERE expires_at < now() " +
        "  LIMIT ?)",
        BATCH_SIZE);
      if (deleted > 0) sleepQuietly(BATCH_PAUSE);
    } while (deleted == BATCH_SIZE
             && System.currentTimeMillis() - start < 60_000);
  }
}
```

Each batch commits in <100ms, releases locks, maintenance pool capped at 2 so can't starve checkout even if misconfigured.
